<section class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-12 md:px-6">
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold">Bridge Fen</h1>

  <iframe class="h-[400px] w-full rounded-lg my-6" loading="lazy" src="https://www.google.com/maps?q=52.3859753,0.27345260000004146&z=16&output=embed" title="Map of Bridge Fen"></iframe>

  <div class="prose-page">
    <p>
      Bridge Fen is the only Ely allotment site that has the famous black fen soil, the other
      sites are on the clay outcrop that forms the Isle of Ely. The soil is rich peat, very light
      and easy to work. It is often described as like gardening on a giant grow-bag. Raised beds
      are not needed because the peat is almost as deep as the cathedral, of which there is a
      spectacular view.<br />
      &nbsp; Unlike the other sites mains water for summer use is not installed at Bridge Fen. The
      site is below sea level, so there is always moisture down in the soil which encourages deep
      root growth. Onsite parking is available.<br />
      &nbsp; An abundance of wildlife can be seen and heard at this site including many species of
      birds. Most plot holders have installed boundary fences to help provide seedlings with
      shelter from the wind and the occasional rabbit.<br />
      &nbsp; &nbsp;See
      <a href="https://www.cambridgeshire.gov.uk/news/donation-of-fresh-vegetables-makes-big-difference-to-community-cafe/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">this link for news of Bridge Fen produce</a>.
    </p>
  </div>

